1
00:00:46,188 --> 00:00:47,308
Umph.

2
00:02:34,281 --> 00:02:36,041
What a location.

3
00:02:36,281 --> 00:02:40,440
Ah, Si. The mighty Coliseum.
The glory of Rome.

4
00:02:41,719 --> 00:02:44,718
Doesn't it stir your imagination?

5
00:02:44,758 --> 00:02:47,718
You bet it does, baby.
Do you people realise

6
00:02:48,317 --> 00:02:50,237
what a shopping centre
we could put up there?

7
00:02:50,677 --> 00:02:52,556
Plenty of parking too.

8
00:03:05,513 --> 00:03:06,792
Here it is, ladies and gentlemen,

9
00:03:07,113 --> 00:03:09,472
the world's highest
office building.

10
00:03:09,513 --> 00:03:14,031
Hawk Plaza... 130 stories
of man-made glory.

11
00:03:14,871 --> 00:03:17,150
In just a few hours,
Hawk Enterprises

12
00:03:17,191 --> 00:03:19,829
will break ground on
this incredible project.

13
00:03:20,070 --> 00:03:22,349
How did it happen,
you ask? I give you

14
00:03:22,350 --> 00:03:24,628
now the man that made
it all possible.

15
00:03:34,345 --> 00:03:36,386
Thank you, friends. Thank you.

16
00:03:37,705 --> 00:03:40,144
My heart is too full to speak.

17
00:03:41,504 --> 00:03:43,143
Ah, you see.

18
00:03:45,183 --> 00:03:48,622
You've brought a tear to
this flinty, old eye.

19
00:03:48,703 --> 00:03:51,262
So, all I can say is thank you.

20
00:03:52,142 --> 00:03:56,500
Thank you for allowing me to share
a moment of your precious time.

21
00:03:59,420 --> 00:04:00,699
Get those deadheads out of here.

22
00:04:00,780 --> 00:04:02,859
What, are they gonna stand around
all day and drink my booze?

23
00:04:02,860 --> 00:04:05,018
All right, ladies and
gentlemen, down to my office...

24
00:04:05,179 --> 00:04:07,417
where a scroll awaits you.

25
00:04:08,777 --> 00:04:09,937
Hello.

26
00:04:09,977 --> 00:04:11,936
Mr. Barnsdorf, sir.

27
00:04:12,017 --> 00:04:13,376
Hello, Barnsdorf.

28
00:04:13,456 --> 00:04:15,655
When are you going to be ready
for us to start digging?

29
00:04:15,736 --> 00:04:17,575
What are you talking about?

30
00:04:17,655 --> 00:04:19,655
That building site's
as clean as a...

31
00:04:22,654 --> 00:04:24,013
What's that?

32
00:04:24,053 --> 00:04:25,914
I thought we got
rid of that crummy

33
00:04:25,915 --> 00:04:27,412
little firehouse months ago.

34
00:04:27,692 --> 00:04:29,725
There's just one
hold-up. We couldn't get

35
00:04:29,726 --> 00:04:31,612
old lady Steinmetz
to sign the papers.

36
00:04:31,691 --> 00:04:34,331
Just one, beat-up old
lady makes monkeys

37
00:04:34,410 --> 00:04:37,770
out of the most overpaid
lawyers in the country.

38
00:04:37,810 --> 00:04:39,712
Come on, boys. I expect a little

39
00:04:39,713 --> 00:04:41,969
action, and I better
get it or else.

40
00:04:42,049 --> 00:04:44,288
For some reason, she
doesn't seem to trust us.

41
00:04:44,608 --> 00:04:48,727
Of course she doesn't. Have
you looked at yourselves?

42
00:04:48,807 --> 00:04:51,487
Your own mothers
wouldn't trust ya.

43
00:04:52,966 --> 00:04:56,205
What we need is somebody
so nauseatingly innocent,

44
00:04:56,285 --> 00:04:58,124
and so stomach-turningly helpful

45
00:04:58,205 --> 00:05:00,285
and so incredibly dumb
anybody would trust him.

46
00:05:00,364 --> 00:05:02,124
What is it?

47
00:05:02,164 --> 00:05:03,684
Mr. Willoughby
Whitfield to see you.

48
00:05:03,883 --> 00:05:05,244
He says he's your nephew.

49
00:05:05,323 --> 00:05:07,482
Whoever he is, throw him out.

50
00:05:07,683 --> 00:05:09,962
Don't bother me again.

51
00:05:10,122 --> 00:05:12,041
Say, wait a minute.

52
00:05:12,082 --> 00:05:15,641
Is that that dumb-looking kid
of my sister's from back east?

53
00:05:15,720 --> 00:05:17,760
He was going to law
school or something?

54
00:05:17,960 --> 00:05:21,959
He just finished law school. He
says he's a full-fledged lawyer.

55
00:05:22,639 --> 00:05:26,318
He's a full-fledged
lawyer. Send him in.

56
00:05:27,438 --> 00:05:28,678
Mr. Hawk will see you now.

57
00:05:28,757 --> 00:05:29,796
Oh.

58
00:05:31,036 --> 00:05:32,316
Thank you.

59
00:05:35,236 --> 00:05:37,115
Come in, boy. Come in.

60
00:05:44,314 --> 00:05:46,473
Isn't he beautiful?

61
00:05:48,833 --> 00:05:52,392
Uncle Alonzo, I hereby present you

62
00:05:52,471 --> 00:05:56,190
with the first law college
Humanitarian-of-the-Year Award.

63
00:05:56,390 --> 00:05:57,390
Here.

64
00:05:57,430 --> 00:05:59,670
Oh, well, well.
Humanitarian of the Year?

65
00:05:59,709 --> 00:06:00,709
That's right, Uncle.

66
00:06:00,789 --> 00:06:03,374
Award committees give
out humanitarian

67
00:06:03,375 --> 00:06:05,628
awards to a lot of strange ducks,

68
00:06:05,708 --> 00:06:06,748
but why me?

69
00:06:06,788 --> 00:06:08,028
I was the award committee.

70
00:06:08,347 --> 00:06:10,106
You put in the fix.

71
00:06:10,187 --> 00:06:12,226
You figured to take care
of your Uncle Alonzo.

72
00:06:12,306 --> 00:06:13,546
You're a smart boy.

73
00:06:13,665 --> 00:06:15,146
If there's one thing I admire,

74
00:06:15,225 --> 00:06:18,105
it's somebody who knows how
to use juice properly.

75
00:06:18,145 --> 00:06:19,225
Juice?

76
00:06:19,265 --> 00:06:21,824
Yes, juice. How to use
muscle, influence,

77
00:06:21,984 --> 00:06:24,103
how to bend things his own way.

78
00:06:24,183 --> 00:06:26,343
Oh, no. My goodness, no.

79
00:06:26,422 --> 00:06:28,662
It wasn't done dishonestly.
I thought it over,

80
00:06:28,702 --> 00:06:33,421
and I couldn't think of anyone
any more deserving than you.

81
00:06:33,461 --> 00:06:35,060
How come?

82
00:06:35,220 --> 00:06:37,620
From the day I was born, my
mother never tired of telling me

83
00:06:37,700 --> 00:06:39,939
what a great man her brother was,

84
00:06:40,019 --> 00:06:43,539
getting rid of dirty old buildings
and building shiny new ones,

85
00:06:43,578 --> 00:06:46,577
sending us California fruit at
Christmas. You were her idol.

86
00:06:47,537 --> 00:06:49,456
You clowns get out of here.

87
00:06:49,537 --> 00:06:54,736
I'm trying to have a nice talk
with my favourite nephew.

88
00:06:55,895 --> 00:06:57,775
When I look into your eyes

89
00:06:57,814 --> 00:07:01,254
and see the shining light
of idealism aglow there,

90
00:07:01,933 --> 00:07:05,453
it makes me young again
and ready for battle.

91
00:07:05,533 --> 00:07:06,533
Battle?

92
00:07:06,573 --> 00:07:07,813
Yes, battle.

93
00:07:07,852 --> 00:07:10,731
It has never been easy
for us idealists.

94
00:07:10,772 --> 00:07:13,049
Now, I'm going to
give you a chance

95
00:07:13,050 --> 00:07:15,010
to put that idealism into play

96
00:07:15,051 --> 00:07:16,930
on your very first job.

97
00:07:17,490 --> 00:07:18,610
Oh.

98
00:07:19,649 --> 00:07:23,048
Picture if you will, a
tough, little old lady,

99
00:07:23,129 --> 00:07:26,767
living in a rundown,
rat-infested firehouse,

100
00:07:26,848 --> 00:07:30,206
standing right in the way of
our latest civic benefaction.

101
00:07:31,286 --> 00:07:34,845
There may be city builders who
might find it in their heart

102
00:07:34,885 --> 00:07:36,765
to be vindictive to this old lady.

103
00:07:36,805 --> 00:07:38,964
They might say that

104
00:07:39,045 --> 00:07:41,246
she feeds on the
misery of the poor

105
00:07:41,247 --> 00:07:43,203
in that forsaken neighbourhood,

106
00:07:44,163 --> 00:07:48,362
that she rolls drunks, that she
teaches small children to steal

107
00:07:49,521 --> 00:07:52,161
and make them bring most
of the take to her.

108
00:07:52,201 --> 00:07:56,760
Would I, Alonzo Hawk,
Humanitarian of the Year,

109
00:07:57,200 --> 00:07:58,879
stoop to such tactics?

110
00:07:58,960 --> 00:08:00,719
On the contrary.

111
00:08:01,279 --> 00:08:03,039
I would do everything in my power

112
00:08:03,118 --> 00:08:06,557
to help that tough,
no-good, little old lady.

113
00:08:06,677 --> 00:08:09,437
I would give her a large sum
for that worthless property,

114
00:08:09,557 --> 00:08:12,636
and I would provide a
special price to her alone

115
00:08:12,676 --> 00:08:15,995
a lifetime lease in
Eternity Towers,

116
00:08:16,075 --> 00:08:17,517
that beautiful new haven for

117
00:08:17,518 --> 00:08:19,474
helpless old people
such as herself.

118
00:08:19,994 --> 00:08:22,194
It has a gymnasium, a sauna,

119
00:08:22,234 --> 00:08:25,913
an old Rudolph Valentino
Sessue Hayakawa movie.

120
00:08:25,953 --> 00:08:28,392
It has a beauty
parlour, hobby centre,

121
00:08:29,112 --> 00:08:32,151
and instead of cooking her
heart out over a hot stove,

122
00:08:32,431 --> 00:08:35,190
there would be automatic
machines in every hall

123
00:08:35,271 --> 00:08:38,629
to lavish her with everything
from pizza to hot chilli.

124
00:08:40,230 --> 00:08:42,215
Now wouldn't it make
just your whole

125
00:08:42,216 --> 00:08:44,148
being happy to be
part of all that?

126
00:08:44,228 --> 00:08:45,428
When can I start, Uncle?

127
00:08:45,508 --> 00:08:46,908
Here's the address. Get moving.

128
00:09:10,222 --> 00:09:12,301
- Here.
- Thanks, pal.

129
00:09:12,341 --> 00:09:13,980
Ah, isn't it breathtaking?

130
00:09:14,540 --> 00:09:16,020
It's a mess, all right.

131
00:09:16,460 --> 00:09:18,099
That guy, Hawk, oughta be hung.

132
00:09:18,180 --> 00:09:19,339
What?

133
00:09:24,618 --> 00:09:26,538
I'm coming.

134
00:09:31,056 --> 00:09:34,535
Mrs. Steinmetz? Good morning. My
name is Willoughby Whitfield.

135
00:09:34,616 --> 00:09:36,335
I'd like to discuss
business with you.

136
00:09:36,415 --> 00:09:37,415
Come in, won't you?

137
00:09:37,416 --> 00:09:38,455
I can't.

138
00:09:38,534 --> 00:09:41,454
You see this car has
rolled onto my foot.

139
00:09:41,533 --> 00:09:43,253
Oh, dear.

140
00:09:43,373 --> 00:09:45,893
I guess somebody forgot to
set the brake or something.

141
00:09:45,932 --> 00:09:47,372
Herbie, aren't you
ashamed of yourself?

142
00:09:47,452 --> 00:09:49,732
Get off Mr. Whitfield's foot.

143
00:09:49,812 --> 00:09:51,651
Herbie's always
trying to protect me.

144
00:09:51,731 --> 00:09:52,731
Herbie?

145
00:09:52,770 --> 00:09:55,810
I'm quite capable of
taking care of myself.

146
00:09:55,890 --> 00:09:58,090
I was about to make
a nice cup of tea.

147
00:09:58,169 --> 00:10:00,289
Come in. You must
have one with me.

148
00:10:00,329 --> 00:10:01,329
Oh, thank you.

149
00:10:03,008 --> 00:10:05,208
Of course, I have
to humour Herbie.

150
00:10:05,247 --> 00:10:07,687
He used to be a famous racing car,

151
00:10:07,767 --> 00:10:10,407
but his driver went to Europe
to drive foreign cars,

152
00:10:10,486 --> 00:10:13,166
so he's a little sensitive.
You can understand that.

153
00:10:13,246 --> 00:10:15,885
Yes. Now, to get down to
business, Mrs. Steinmetz.

154
00:10:15,965 --> 00:10:18,525
People have been worrying about
you living in this old firetrap.

155
00:10:18,564 --> 00:10:20,204
I've been asked to
come over and...

156
00:10:20,284 --> 00:10:22,843
Firehouse, not firetrap.

157
00:10:22,883 --> 00:10:25,402
Firehouse, yes. Be that as it may,

158
00:10:25,483 --> 00:10:26,802
the least we can do...

159
00:10:29,642 --> 00:10:31,801
Stop that. That's downright rude.

160
00:10:34,161 --> 00:10:35,960
Do you know what he was playing?

161
00:10:36,680 --> 00:10:39,799
Do Not Trust Him, Gentle
Maiden. Nothing personal.

162
00:10:39,879 --> 00:10:40,879
No.

163
00:10:40,880 --> 00:10:42,519
He's a friend of
Herbie's, of course.

164
00:10:42,678 --> 00:10:43,718
Friend of Herbie's?

165
00:10:43,998 --> 00:10:45,678
So is old 22.

166
00:10:47,197 --> 00:10:50,076
You may as well meet all the
family while you're here.

167
00:10:50,156 --> 00:10:53,076
Number 22 used to be on
the old Clay Street line.

168
00:10:56,235 --> 00:10:57,715
Herbie found him in a vacant lot.

169
00:10:57,754 --> 00:10:59,794
Someone had used him
as a chicken house.

170
00:10:59,834 --> 00:11:01,714
He's much happier here, of course.

171
00:11:03,193 --> 00:11:05,712
I can understand that you may have

172
00:11:05,752 --> 00:11:07,792
some emotional attachment
to this old building...

173
00:11:07,832 --> 00:11:09,551
Indeed, I have.

174
00:11:10,671 --> 00:11:12,710
I was married here
to my late husband,

175
00:11:12,751 --> 00:11:15,358
Captain Steinmetz, of the San
Francisco Fire Department.

176
00:11:15,359 --> 00:11:16,359
Oh?

177
00:11:16,360 --> 00:11:18,109
One of the heroes
of the great fire.

178
00:11:18,269 --> 00:11:20,375
We understand your
position. That's

179
00:11:20,376 --> 00:11:22,188
why Mr. Hawk has authorised...

180
00:11:22,228 --> 00:11:23,947
Don't tell me you're
from Alonzo Hawk?

181
00:11:23,988 --> 00:11:25,028
Yes.

182
00:11:25,067 --> 00:11:26,187
Oh, you have such a nice face.

183
00:11:26,268 --> 00:11:27,268
Thank you.

184
00:11:27,307 --> 00:11:30,706
Not at all like those
ruffians he usually sends.

185
00:11:30,787 --> 00:11:34,665
If you would just look at
the size of this check.

186
00:11:34,745 --> 00:11:37,305
I don't know anything about money.

187
00:11:37,384 --> 00:11:40,823
My nephew, Tennessee Steinmetz,
usually takes care of me.

188
00:11:40,904 --> 00:11:42,263
He used to live here.

189
00:11:42,343 --> 00:11:45,703
He had to rush off to Tibet
because his guru got sick.

190
00:11:45,742 --> 00:11:48,822
If you would just look at
this... What's a guru?

191
00:11:48,901 --> 00:11:53,020
His teacher. My nephew is a
student of Oriental Philosophy.

192
00:11:53,060 --> 00:11:56,380
That's how he learned that
things have an inner life.

193
00:11:56,500 --> 00:12:00,739
Like wind, rain, traffic lights,
can openers, flowers...

194
00:12:00,779 --> 00:12:02,658
And little cars.

195
00:12:02,698 --> 00:12:05,657
That's how Herbie and Tennessee
became such great friends.

196
00:12:05,697 --> 00:12:07,507
Mrs. Steinmetz, this
sum of money could

197
00:12:07,508 --> 00:12:09,496
take care of you for
the rest of your life.

198
00:12:09,537 --> 00:12:13,175
I didn't have to study Oriental
Philosophy the way Tennessee did.

199
00:12:13,215 --> 00:12:14,815
I could talk to Herbie right off.

200
00:12:14,855 --> 00:12:15,855
Oh?

201
00:12:15,895 --> 00:12:17,215
I guess it's in the blood.

202
00:12:20,534 --> 00:12:22,133
See ya tomorrow.

203
00:12:24,572 --> 00:12:26,812
I don't like to press,
but believe me,

204
00:12:26,892 --> 00:12:28,732
Mr. Hawk has your
interest at heart.

205
00:12:28,772 --> 00:12:30,891
I have an agreement here.
If you would just glance...

206
00:12:30,971 --> 00:12:32,411
Oh, Nicole.

207
00:12:32,491 --> 00:12:35,010
I want you to meet a
gentleman from Mr. Hawk's.

208
00:12:35,090 --> 00:12:37,290
- How do you do?
- Agh.

209
00:12:40,209 --> 00:12:43,288
Poor Mr. Whitfield.
Such a nice young man.

210
00:12:43,887 --> 00:12:45,687
They're bothering us again?

211
00:12:45,727 --> 00:12:47,127
You've hurt your hand.

212
00:12:48,286 --> 00:12:51,566
On the contrary, it
feels marvellous.

213
00:12:52,405 --> 00:12:53,765
Are you all right, Mr. Whitfield?

214
00:12:53,846 --> 00:12:55,205
What was that?

215
00:12:55,285 --> 00:12:59,364
Nicole Harris, a very brave young
lady. She works for the airline.

216
00:12:59,444 --> 00:13:01,465
Last week she knocked
out a hijacker

217
00:13:01,466 --> 00:13:03,323
with a bottle of California wine.

218
00:13:03,403 --> 00:13:06,322
Now, get out. If you or any more
of Hawk's stooges come around,

219
00:13:06,362 --> 00:13:07,922
you'll get worse than that.

220
00:13:08,002 --> 00:13:12,041
Please. Mr. Whitfield and I were
having a nice conversation.

221
00:13:12,241 --> 00:13:14,320
I'll bet. But...

222
00:13:14,400 --> 00:13:18,159
Isn't it time for your nap?
Mr. Whitfield is just going.

223
00:13:18,839 --> 00:13:22,238
Well, very well.
Goodbye, Mr. Whitfield.

224
00:13:22,318 --> 00:13:23,917
I hope I'll see you
again when I come down.

225
00:13:23,998 --> 00:13:25,037
Mrs. Steinmetz...

226
00:13:25,077 --> 00:13:26,397
- Out. Out.
- What?

227
00:13:27,756 --> 00:13:29,524
Please, have a heart.
This is my first

228
00:13:29,525 --> 00:13:31,156
assignment. I can't
afford to fail.

229
00:13:31,595 --> 00:13:34,115
I said, out.

230
00:13:35,355 --> 00:13:36,515
All right, all right.

231
00:13:44,873 --> 00:13:46,992
Miss, you look like
a sensible person.

232
00:13:47,072 --> 00:13:49,991
You must know living all alone
in this crummy neighbourhood

233
00:13:50,071 --> 00:13:51,630
is no place for an elderly woman.

234
00:13:51,910 --> 00:13:53,670
What do you mean
"alone"? She's got me...

235
00:13:54,310 --> 00:13:56,269
And she's got Herbie.

236
00:13:56,350 --> 00:13:57,630
That's another thing.

237
00:13:57,669 --> 00:13:59,518
That goofy story about this car,

238
00:13:59,519 --> 00:14:01,828
that's a sure sign
she's coming apart.

239
00:14:02,149 --> 00:14:03,547
So you think it's goofy?

240
00:14:03,588 --> 00:14:04,748
Of course, don't you?

241
00:14:07,027 --> 00:14:09,506
How would you like to
go for a little ride?

242
00:14:10,746 --> 00:14:11,986
I thought you didn't like me?

243
00:14:12,266 --> 00:14:16,184
I'd like to take you for a ride in
Herbie. I'd like that very much.

244
00:14:16,225 --> 00:14:17,664
That's very nice of you.

245
00:14:18,464 --> 00:14:20,023
I'll be ready in a minute.

246
00:14:35,700 --> 00:14:37,779
All right, Herbie.
Let's get going.

247
00:14:37,819 --> 00:14:40,618
Miss Harris, you're obviously
an intelligent young woman.

248
00:14:40,698 --> 00:14:43,818
Why do you pretend to talk to
this car? People might wonder.

249
00:14:44,218 --> 00:14:46,017
Don't listen to him,
Herbie. Just move it.

250
00:14:46,097 --> 00:14:48,897
I can understand Mrs. Steinmetz
thinking of this car as a person.

251
00:14:48,976 --> 00:14:50,685
Old age has many
fantasies. It only

252
00:14:50,686 --> 00:14:52,535
proves that she needs
Mr. Hawk's help.

